window.EMPACT_DATA = {"manifest":{"id":"empact","title":"EMPACT — Emergency Medical Patients: Assessment, Care & Transport","subtitle":"The Ultimate Course Reviewer","version":"1.0.0","edition":"Systematic medical-patient assessment for EMS providers","description":"A comprehensive, self-contained study reviewer for the systematic assessment and management of the medical patient. Each chapter includes a concise summary, clinical pearls, red flags, common mistakes, memory aids, decision trees, high-yield flashcards, differential-diagnosis quiz questions, and realistic patient scenarios. Built for EMTs, paramedics, and nursing/PA students who need to move from possibilities to probabilities at the bedside.","icon":"stethoscope","color":"#1f6feb","accentColor":"#c8102e","estimatedHours":10,"difficulty":"Intermediate","certification":null,"examLink":"empact.html","audience":["EMT","AEMT","Paramedic","Nursing Student","PA Student"],"prerequisites":["Basic anatomy and physiology","BLS provider competency"],"contentTypes":["summary","flashcards","quizzes","scenarios","algorithms","tables"],"chapters":[{"id":"c01","number":1,"title":"The Systematic Approach & Differential Diagnosis","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c02","number":2,"title":"Airway Management in the Medical Patient","section":"Airway & Breathing","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c03","number":3,"title":"Respiratory Emergencies","section":"Airway & Breathing","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c04","number":4,"title":"Cardiovascular Emergencies","section":"Cardiovascular","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c05","number":5,"title":"Shock Recognition & Management","section":"Cardiovascular","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c06","number":6,"title":"Neurological Emergencies","section":"Neurological","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c07","number":7,"title":"Endocrine Emergencies","section":"Metabolic","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c08","number":8,"title":"Abdominal & Gastrointestinal Emergencies","section":"Abdominal","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c09","number":9,"title":"Infectious Disease, Sepsis & Anaphylaxis","section":"Immune & Infectious","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c10","number":10,"title":"Oncologic & Special Medical Considerations","section":"Special Topics","difficulty":"Intermediate"}]},"chapters":{"c01":{"id":"c01","title":"The Systematic Approach & Differential Diagnosis","shortTitle":"Systematic Approach","estimatedStudyTime":28,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["Describe the four stages of patient assessment: scene size-up, primary assessment, secondary assessment, reassessment.","Explain the concept of differential diagnosis as moving from possibilities to probabilities.","State the relative contribution of history versus physical exam in the medical patient.","Explain why life threats are identified and treated before a detailed history is taken.","Describe scene safety considerations specific to medical calls.","Explain why activities of daily living (ADLs) matter in medical assessment."],"summary":[{"title":"Differential Diagnosis: Possibilities to Probabilities","content":"Differential diagnosis is the process of narrowing a wide field of possible causes for a patient's presentation down to the most probable one (or few) explanations. It is not about reaching a single certain diagnosis in the field — it is about building an organized list of what could be happening, then using the history, physical exam, and vital signs to raise or lower the likelihood of each possibility, so that treatment and transport decisions are appropriately targeted."},{"title":"The Four Stages of Assessment","content":"Assessment proceeds through four stages. Scene size-up: initial observations for safety, standard precautions, the nature of the illness, and clues to the cause, performed before patient contact. Primary assessment: forming a general impression, determining level of consciousness, and identifying and treating immediate life threats (airway, breathing, circulation) — this stage also sets the patient's overall priority. Secondary assessment: a focused or detailed history, physical examination, and vital signs. Reassessment: ongoing monitoring, repeated more frequently in unstable patients, tracking trends and response to treatment."},{"title":"History Dominates in the Medical Patient","content":"For the medical patient, approximately 80% of the diagnostic information comes from the history, and only about 20% from the physical examination — the reverse emphasis from many trauma presentations. This means a structured, unhurried history (chief complaint, history of present illness, past medical history, medications, allergies) is often the single highest-yield tool available in the field. Active listening — getting on the patient's level and asking follow-up questions — is what makes that history useful."},{"title":"Life Threats First, Always","content":"Regardless of how compelling the history sounds, the primary assessment's job is to identify and treat immediate threats to airway, breathing, and circulation before proceeding to a detailed history and exam. A patient in respiratory failure or shock needs intervention now, not a complete past medical history first. This ordering — treat what will kill first — is the organizing principle underneath every other assessment skill in this course."},{"title":"Scene Safety and Pattern Recognition on Medical Calls","content":"Medical calls carry their own scene-safety considerations: standard precautions against blood and body fluids, awareness of the environment (hoarding, aggressive family members, drug paraphernalia), and — critically — recognizing when more than one person at a scene has the same signs and symptoms. A cluster of similarly ill people is a red flag for a shared environmental or toxic exposure (carbon monoxide, a gas leak, a common food source) rather than several unrelated coincidental illnesses, and should prompt inquiry into a shared cause before entering blindly."},{"title":"Why People Call: Activities of Daily Living","content":"Patients and families often call EMS not because a specific diagnosis has changed, but because the patient's Activities of Daily Living (ADLs) — the ability to walk, eat, dress, toilet, or think clearly — have become altered by illness. Asking 'what is different today compared to your usual baseline?' surfaces this functional change and is often more revealing than asking for a self-diagnosis, especially in patients who cannot articulate their complaint precisely (young children, patients with dementia, non-verbal patients)."}],"clinicalPearls":["Differential diagnosis is going from possibilities to probabilities — not guessing a single answer.","Always identify and treat life threats first (Airway — Breathing — Circulation).","In the medical patient, about 80% of the information comes from the history and 20% from the physical examination.","Always trust YOUR exam — your own primary assessment and findings, not just what you're told.","The key to active listening is getting on your patient's level and asking follow-up questions.","If more than one person presents with the same signs and symptoms, inquire about a shared cause."],"redFlags":["Skipping the primary assessment's life-threat check to jump straight into history-taking.","Multiple patients at one location with the same symptoms — treat as a possible shared exposure until ruled out.","Discounting your own physical findings in favor of a chief complaint that doesn't match what you're seeing."],"commonMistakes":["Treating assessment as a single event instead of a continuous, four-stage process with reassessment.","Spending exam time on find-everything physical exams when the history would answer the question faster.","Asking closed yes/no questions instead of open-ended questions that invite the patient to describe their own experience."],"memoryAids":["Possibilities → Probabilities: that is what 'differential diagnosis' means.","Size-up, Primary, Secondary, Reassess — the four assessment stages, in order.","History 80%, exam 20% — for the medical patient, listen first.","ADLs changed = why they called: what's different today?"],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"The Four Stages of Patient Assessment","content":"Arrive on scene\n  → Scene size-up: safety, precautions, nature of illness, clues\n  → Primary assessment: general impression, LOC, identify/treat life threats (A-B-C), assign priority\n     → Life threat found: treat immediately before proceeding\n  → Secondary assessment: focused/detailed history + physical exam + vital signs\n     → Build differential diagnosis: possibilities → probabilities\n  → Reassessment: repeat, more frequently if unstable; track trends and response to treatment"}],"references":["National EMS Education Standards — Assessment domain (systematic patient assessment)","EMPACT clinical pearls collection — Core Concepts and Assessment"]}},"flashcards":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cards":[{"id":"c01_fc01","question":"What is differential diagnosis?","answer":"The process of narrowing a wide field of possible causes down to the most probable explanation(s) — going from possibilities to probabilities.","category":"Core Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc02","question":"What is the highest priority in the primary assessment?","answer":"Identifying and treating life threats first — airway, breathing, circulation — before proceeding to history and exam.","category":"Core Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc03","question":"What roughly is the split between history and physical exam value in the medical patient?","answer":"About 80% of the information comes from the history and about 20% from the physical examination.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc04","question":"What does scene size-up include?","answer":"Initial observations for safety, standard precautions, the nature of the illness, and clues to the cause.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc05","question":"What does the primary assessment establish?","answer":"General impression, level of consciousness, identification/treatment of life threats (A-B-C), and the patient's overall priority.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc06","question":"What does the secondary assessment consist of?","answer":"History, physical examination, and vital signs.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc07","question":"What is reassessment and when is it done more frequently?","answer":"Ongoing assessment to track trends and response to treatment; done more frequently in unstable patients.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc08","question":"What is the key to active listening in a patient interview?","answer":"Getting on your patient's level and asking follow-up questions.","category":"Clinical Pearls"},{"id":"c01_fc09","question":"Why should you 'trust YOUR exam'?","answer":"Your own primary assessment and findings are the most reliable data you have — don't discount them in favor of a chief complaint that doesn't match what you observe.","category":"Clinical Pearls"},{"id":"c01_fc10","question":"What should you consider if multiple people at one scene share the same signs and symptoms?","answer":"A shared environmental or toxic cause (e.g., carbon monoxide, gas leak, common food source) rather than coincidental separate illnesses — inquire about a shared cause.","category":"Safety/Scene"},{"id":"c01_fc11","question":"What are Activities of Daily Living (ADLs)?","answer":"Basic functional activities — walking, eating, dressing, toileting, thinking clearly — whose alteration by illness is often why people call EMS.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc12","question":"What question surfaces an ADL-based functional change?","answer":"'What is different today compared to your usual baseline?'","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc13","question":"In a conscious medical patient exam, what comes first — questions or physical exam?","answer":"Ask questions first, then perform a physical exam directed by the answers.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc14","question":"Why is history so valuable in patients who cannot self-diagnose (children, dementia, non-verbal patients)?","answer":"Asking about functional/ADL changes from baseline reveals what's wrong even when the patient cannot describe or name a specific complaint.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc15","question":"Why treat life threats before taking a full history?","answer":"A patient in respiratory failure or shock needs immediate intervention — a complete history can wait, but airway/breathing/circulation failure cannot.","category":"Core Concepts"}]}},"quizzes":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","questions":[{"id":"c01_q01","question":"What best describes the process of differential diagnosis in the field?","options":["A. Guessing the single correct diagnosis immediately","B. Narrowing a wide field of possible causes down to the most probable explanation(s)","C. Only ruling out cardiac causes","D. Waiting for hospital lab results before forming any impression"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Differential diagnosis is a process — moving from possibilities to probabilities using history, exam, and vitals — not a single instant guess.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q02","question":"Which stage of assessment identifies and treats immediate life threats?","options":["A. Scene size-up","B. Primary assessment","C. Secondary assessment","D. Reassessment"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The primary assessment establishes a general impression, level of consciousness, and identifies/treats airway, breathing, and circulation threats, also setting patient priority.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q03","question":"In the medical patient, approximately what percentage of diagnostic information comes from the history?","options":["A. 20%","B. 50%","C. 80%","D. 100%"],"correct":2,"rationale":"For medical patients, roughly 80% of the diagnostic information comes from the history, with about 20% from the physical exam — the reverse emphasis often seen in trauma.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q04","question":"What should you do first when encountering a patient with an airway obstruction, before taking their full history?","options":["A. Ask about past medical history","B. Treat the airway threat immediately","C. Obtain a complete medication list","D. Perform a detailed head-to-toe exam"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Life threats are treated first, regardless of how much history remains to be taken — airway, breathing, and circulation problems are addressed immediately in the primary assessment.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q05","question":"You arrive at an apartment and find three family members all reporting headache, nausea, and dizziness that began around the same time. What should you suspect?","options":["A. Three unrelated coincidental illnesses","B. A possible shared environmental/toxic exposure (e.g., carbon monoxide)","C. Anxiety spreading socially","D. Nothing unusual — treat each in isolation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"When multiple people share the same signs and symptoms, a common cause such as CO, a gas leak, or a shared food source should be suspected and investigated before entering blindly.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q06","question":"What is included in the secondary assessment?","options":["A. Scene safety only","B. History, physical examination, and vital signs","C. Airway management exclusively","D. Transport decision only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The secondary assessment gathers history, performs a physical exam, and obtains vital signs — building the data needed for the differential diagnosis.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q07","question":"Why is reassessment performed more frequently in unstable patients?","options":["A. To satisfy documentation requirements","B. To track trends and detect deterioration or response to treatment promptly","C. It is not actually more frequent","D. Because unstable patients complain more"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Frequent reassessment in unstable patients catches trends — improving or worsening — allowing timely intervention changes.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q08","question":"A family calls EMS saying their elderly father 'just isn't himself' but cannot name a specific complaint. What is the most useful question?","options":["A. 'Do you have chest pain?' only","B. 'What is different today compared to his usual baseline?'","C. 'What is his diagnosis?'","D. No further questions are needed"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Asking about functional change from baseline (ADLs) often surfaces the real problem, especially when the patient or family cannot self-diagnose.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q09","question":"What does 'trust YOUR exam' mean in patient assessment?","options":["A. Ignore the patient's reported history entirely","B. Give weight to your own primary assessment and findings rather than discounting them in favor of a mismatched complaint","C. Only trust findings confirmed by a second provider","D. Physical exam findings are never reliable"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Your direct findings from the primary assessment are a critical, reliable data source — a mismatched or vague chief complaint shouldn't override what you actually observe.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q10","question":"What is the correct order of the four stages of patient assessment?","options":["A. Primary, scene size-up, secondary, reassessment","B. Scene size-up, primary assessment, secondary assessment, reassessment","C. Secondary, primary, reassessment, scene size-up","D. Reassessment, scene size-up, primary, secondary"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The stages proceed scene size-up → primary assessment → secondary assessment → reassessment, each building on the last.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q11","question":"Why does the key to active listening involve getting on the patient's level?","options":["A. It has no real effect on communication","B. It builds rapport and comfort, encouraging fuller, more accurate answers to follow-up questions","C. It is only a courtesy with no clinical value","D. It replaces the need for physical exam"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Physical positioning and engaged follow-up questions improve the quality and completeness of the history — the highest-yield tool in medical assessment.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q12","question":"Which best explains why ADLs (Activities of Daily Living) matter in medical assessment?","options":["A. They are irrelevant to EMS calls","B. A change in ADLs (walking, eating, dressing, thinking) is often the actual reason a call was made, even without a named diagnosis","C. ADLs only matter for pediatric patients","D. ADLs replace the need for vital signs"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Patients and families frequently call because functional status has changed, not because a diagnosis was made — asking about ADL changes captures this directly.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q13","question":"During assessment of a conscious medical patient, what is the recommended order?","options":["A. Physical exam first, then questions","B. Ask questions first, then perform a directed physical exam","C. Vital signs only, skip both history and exam","D. Simultaneously perform exam and questions with no particular order"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Given history's outsized diagnostic value in medical patients, asking questions first lets the subsequent physical exam be targeted and efficient.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q14","question":"A crew skips checking for life threats and goes straight into a 10-minute history. What is the risk?","options":["A. None — history is more important than life threats","B. A time-critical airway, breathing, or circulation problem may go untreated while history is gathered","C. This is the recommended approach for all patients","D. It only matters for trauma patients"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Regardless of history's diagnostic value, life threats must be identified and treated first — delaying this for history-taking risks patient deterioration.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q15","question":"Which scenario best demonstrates appropriate use of the differential-diagnosis approach?","options":["A. Assuming a single cause immediately and ignoring new exam findings","B. Building a list of possible causes, then using history/exam/vitals to raise or lower the likelihood of each","C. Never forming any clinical impression until arrival at the hospital","D. Diagnosing definitively in the field every time"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The differential-diagnosis approach is iterative: a list of possibilities is narrowed by evidence, not fixed on a single early guess or deferred entirely.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c01_q16","question":"What is the primary purpose of the scene size-up on a medical call?","options":["A. To begin taking vital signs early","B. To assess safety, apply standard precautions, and identify clues to the nature of the illness before patient contact","C. To determine transport destination","D. To complete documentation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Scene size-up happens before hands-on patient care and focuses on safety, precautions, and situational clues — protecting the responder and informing the coming assessment.","difficulty":"Easy"}]}},"scenarios":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cases":[{"id":"c01_s01","title":"Not Himself Today","presentation":"You are called to a home for an 84-year-old man whose daughter says, 'He's just not himself today.' He has no specific complaint, is alert but slower to answer than usual, and his vital signs are within his normal range.","vitals":{"hr":"76 bpm","bp":"134/82 mmHg","rr":"16 bpm","spo2":"97%","loc":"Alert, slower responses"},"question":"What is the most useful next question to ask?","options":["A: 'Do you have chest pain?' and nothing else.","B: 'What is different about him today compared to his usual baseline?'","C: No further questions are needed since vitals are normal.","D: Ask only about his medication list."],"correct":1,"explanation":"With normal vitals and no specific complaint, the change in ADLs/baseline function is the real clue. Asking what's different from baseline can surface subtle findings (early stroke, infection, metabolic change) that a single closed question would miss.","clinicalPearl":"Activities of Daily Living that are altered is often exactly why people call EMS — ask what's different today."},{"id":"c01_s02","title":"Three Sick at the Same Table","presentation":"You respond to a restaurant where three coworkers who ate lunch together are now nauseated, dizzy, and complaining of headache within the same 30-minute window. No trauma is involved.","vitals":{"patient1_hr":"98 bpm","patient2_hr":"102 bpm","patient3_hr":"94 bpm","symptoms":"Nausea, dizziness, headache in all three"},"question":"What should you specifically investigate?","options":["A: Treat each patient as an isolated, unrelated case.","B: Inquire about a shared cause — common food, a gas leak, or another environmental exposure (e.g., carbon monoxide) affecting all three.","C: Assume food poisoning and transport without further scene assessment.","D: Ignore the pattern since vitals are only mildly abnormal."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Multiple people with the same signs and symptoms at one scene is a red flag for a shared cause rather than coincidence. Investigating a common source (shared meal, gas leak, CO) protects both patients and responders before further exposure occurs.","clinicalPearl":"Same symptoms, same time, same place, different people — think shared cause, not coincidence."},{"id":"c01_s03","title":"History First, Then Hands","presentation":"A 55-year-old woman is conscious, alert, and reports intermittent chest discomfort over the past two days. She is calm, breathing comfortably, and hemodynamically stable on your primary assessment.","vitals":{"hr":"82 bpm","bp":"128/78 mmHg","rr":"16 bpm","spo2":"98%","loc":"Alert"},"question":"Given no immediate life threats, what is the recommended assessment sequence?","options":["A: Perform a full head-to-toe physical exam before asking any questions.","B: Ask a directed history (onset, quality, duration, associated symptoms) first, then perform a physical exam guided by her answers.","C: Skip the history since vitals are stable.","D: Transport immediately without further assessment."],"correct":1,"explanation":"With no primary-assessment life threats, the recommended approach is history first — it carries about 80% of the diagnostic value in medical patients — followed by a physical exam directed by what the history reveals, rather than an undirected full exam.","clinicalPearl":"No life threat found? Let the history lead the exam, not the other way around."}]}},"algorithms":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","algorithms":[{"id":"c01_alg01","title":"Systematic Patient Assessment Sequence","description":"The four-stage assessment framework applied to every medical patient encounter.","steps":["Scene size-up: assess safety, apply standard precautions, note the nature of the illness and scene clues before contact.","Primary assessment: form a general impression, determine level of consciousness, identify and treat life threats (airway, breathing, circulation), and assign patient priority.","Secondary assessment: obtain a directed history (history dominates in medical patients), perform a focused physical exam, and obtain vital signs.","Build and refine a differential diagnosis: move from possibilities toward probabilities using the gathered information.","Reassessment: repeat the key elements on an ongoing basis, more frequently if the patient is unstable, tracking trends and treatment response."]}]}},"tables":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","tables":[{"id":"c01_t01","title":"The Four Stages of Assessment","headers":["Stage","Purpose","Key Actions"],"rows":[["Scene size-up","Protect responders; gather scene clues","Safety check, standard precautions, nature-of-illness clues"],["Primary assessment","Find and treat life threats","General impression, LOC, A-B-C threats, assign priority"],["Secondary assessment","Build the differential diagnosis","History, physical exam, vital signs"],["Reassessment","Track trends and treatment response","Repeat key elements; more frequent if unstable"]]},{"id":"c01_t02","title":"Diagnostic Value: History vs Physical Exam (Medical Patient)","headers":["Source","Approximate Contribution"],"rows":[["History","~80%"],["Physical examination","~20%"]]}]}}};
